{
  "texts": [
    "In the context of a priority map, attentional priority refers to the relative strength of activation at each location of the map.",
    "→ Priority map Attentional strategy A mental plan, or policy, guiding how attentional control is used in an attempt to satisfy task goals.",
    "Strategies can sometimes lead to establishing a specific target template, but they can also consist of more abstract policies, such as \"search for the most valuable target,\" \"search through the less numerous subset of stimuli,\" or \"withhold saccadic eye movements until the target is located covertly.\"",
    "→ Templates and strategies Attentional suppression Any mechanism by which the attentional processing of a stimulus/location/time is reduced relative to a specific reference point.",
    "This could be at the level of an absolute feature (first-order suppression), at the level of salience within a feature dimension (second-order suppression) or at a global salience level (→ Features)."
  ]
}